We want to find the eigenvector of

\begin{align*}
A=\begin{bmatrix}
2  &  1  &  1\\
1  &  2  &  1\\
1  &  1  &  2
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

with eigenvalue $\lambda=4$. We therefore want to find the vector
$\mathbf{x}=[a,b,c]^T$ such that

\begin{align*}
(A-4I)\mathbf{x}=
\begin{bmatrix}
-2  &  1  &  1\\
1  & - 2  &  1\\
1  &  1  & - 2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
a\\
b\\
c
\end{bmatrix}
=\mathbf{0}\end{align*}

We therefore have three equations with three unknowns

\begin{align*}
-2a+b+c&=0\\
a-2b+c&=0\\
a+b-2c&=0\end{align*}

We can solve the first equation for c to get

\begin{align*}
c=2a-b\end{align*}

and can sub this into the second equation to get

\begin{align*}
a-2b+2a-b&=0\\
3a-3b&=0\\
b&=a.\end{align*}

Using c=2a-b and b=a we conclude that c=a. From the last equation we
get,

\begin{align*}
a+a-2a=0\end{align*}

which is satisfied for all a. Therefore, let a=1 without loss of
generality. This implies that b=c=1 as well. Therefore the eigenvector
for the eigenvalue 4 is

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Of course, any multiple of this is also an eigenvector (expect
multiplying by 0).
